{"title_page": "The Restoration Game", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| name           = The Restoration Game \n| image          =  \n| caption        =  \n| alt            =  \n| author         = [[Ken MacLeod]]\n| genre          =science fiction/[[techno-thriller]] novel\n| publisher      =  \n| pub_date       = 2010 \n}}\n'''''The Restoration Game''''' is a 2010 science fiction/[[techno-thriller]] novel by [[Ken MacLeod]].\n\nThe novel's main character and narrator, Lucy Stone, a computer programmer, grew up in the fictional Caucasian Soviet republic of Krassnia and in 2008 works for a videogame company in Edinburgh.<ref name=\"ft\">{{Cite news|last=Lovegrove|first=James|title=The Restoration Game|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/3a11008e-9069-11df-ad26-00144feab49a.html|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|date=19 July 2010}}</ref>  After Stone's mother, who once worked for the CIA, commissions her company to create an [[MMORPG]] based on Krassnian mythology, Stone becomes entangled in the region's politics and her own family history.<ref name=\"ft\" /><ref name=\"focus\">{{Cite news|last=Wright|first=Jonathan|title=The Restoration Game |url=http://www.bbcfocusmagazine.com/review/restoration-game|newspaper=[[BBC Focus]]}}</ref>\n\nThe story is set in the year 2008.<ref name=\"sfx\">{{Cite news|last=Wright|first=Jonathan|title=The Restoration Game \u2013 Ken MacLeod|url=http://www.sfx.co.uk/2010/07/02/book-review-the-restoration-game/|newspaper=[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]|date=2 July 2010}}</ref>  MacLeod has said that he originally intended to set it in the near future, but the [[2008 South Ossetia war]] made this impossible.<ref name=\"blog\">http://kenmacleod.blogspot.com/2009/03/what-ive-been-doing.html</ref><ref>http://www.sfcrowsnest.com/articles/features/2009/A-Mid-Day-Session-Ken-Macleod-interviewed-14005.php</ref>\n\nReviews of the novel have generally been positive.<ref name=\"ft\" /><ref name=\"focus\" /><ref name=\"sfx\" /><ref name=\"walker\">{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Jesse|title=Briefly Noted: It's All in the Game|url=http://reason.com/archives/2010/08/21/its-all-in-the-game|newspaper=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]|date=October 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"scotsman\">http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/entertainment/Book-reviews-New-Model-Army.6373252.jp</ref><ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/mar/13/science-fiction-roundup-eric-brown | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Science fiction & fantasy roundup | first=Eric | last=Brown | date=13 March 2010}}</ref>  ''Financial Times'' reviewer James Lovegrove writes that \"Where his novel excels is in its depiction of the machinations used both by governments and families to coerce others into doing their bidding, and in its inquiry into the nature of reality.\"<ref name=\"ft\" />\n\nThe novel was nominated for the [[Prometheus Award]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Libertarian Futurist Society|title=PROMETHEUS AWARD FINALISTS ANNOUNCED|url=http://lfs.org/releases/2012PrometheusFinalists.shtml|accessdate=10 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Simulated reality]]\n* [[Simulated reality in fiction]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{isfdb title|id=1075882}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Restoration Game}}\n[[Category:Novels by Ken MacLeod]]\n[[Category:2010 British novels]]\n[[Category:2010 science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 2008]]\n[[Category:Libertarian science fiction]]\n[[Category:British science fiction novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| name           = The Restoration Game \n| image          =  \n| caption        =  \n| alt            =  \n| author         = [[Ken MacLeod]]\n| genre          =science fiction/[[techno-thriller]] novel\n| publisher      =  \n| pub_date       = 2010 \n}}\n'''''The Restoration Game''''' is a 2010 science fiction/[[techno-thriller]] novel by [[Ken MacLeod]].\n\nThe novel's main character and narrator, Lucy Stone, a computer programmer, grew up in the fictional Caucasian Soviet republic of Krassnia and in 2008 works for a videogame company in Edinburgh.<ref name=\"ft\">{{Cite news|last=Lovegrove|first=James|title=The Restoration Game|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/3a11008e-9069-11df-ad26-00144feab49a.html|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|date=19 July 2010}}</ref>  After Stone's mother, who once worked for the CIA, commissions her company to create an [[MMORPG]] based on Krassnian mythology, Stone becomes entangled in the region's politics and her own family history.<ref name=\"ft\" /><ref name=\"focus\">{{Cite news|last=Wright|first=Jonathan|title=The Restoration Game |url=http://www.bbcfocusmagazine.com/review/restoration-game|newspaper=[[BBC Focus]]}}</ref>\n\nThe story is set in the year 2008.<ref name=\"sfx\">{{Cite news|last=Wright|first=Jonathan|title=The Restoration Game \u2013 Ken MacLeod|url=http://www.sfx.co.uk/2010/07/02/book-review-the-restoration-game/|newspaper=[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]|date=2 July 2010}}</ref>  MacLeod has said that he originally intended to set it in the near future, but the [[2008 South Ossetia war]] made this impossible.<ref name=\"blog\">http://kenmacleod.blogspot.com/2009/03/what-ive-been-doing.html</ref><ref>http://www.sfcrowsnest.com/articles/features/2009/A-Mid-Day-Session-Ken-Macleod-interviewed-14005.php</ref>\n\nReviews of the novel have generally been positive.<ref name=\"ft\" /><ref name=\"focus\" /><ref name=\"sfx\" /><ref name=\"walker\">{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Jesse|title=Briefly Noted: It's All in the Game|url=http://reason.com/archives/2010/08/21/its-all-in-the-game|newspaper=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]|date=October 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"scotsman\">http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/entertainment/Book-reviews-New-Model-Army.6373252.jp</ref><ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/mar/13/science-fiction-roundup-eric-brown | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Science fiction & fantasy roundup | first=Eric | last=Brown | date=13 March 2010}}</ref>  ''Financial Times'' reviewer James Lovegrove writes that \"Where his novel excels is in its depiction of the machinations used both by governments and families to coerce others into doing their bidding, and in its inquiry into the nature of reality.\"<ref name=\"ft\" />\n\nThe novel was nominated for the [[Prometheus Award]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Libertarian Futurist Society|title=PROMETHEUS AWARD FINALISTS ANNOUNCED|url=http://lfs.org/releases/2012PrometheusFinalists.shtml|accessdate=10 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Simulated reality]]\n* [[Simulated reality in fiction]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n==External links==\n*{{isfdb title|id=1075882}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Restoration Game}}\n[[Category:Novels by Ken MacLeod]]\n[[Category:2010 British novels]]\n[[Category:2010 science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 2008]]\n[[Category:Libertarian science fiction]]\n[[Category:British science fiction novels]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag and add authority control template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Restoration_Game"}
