deployed =\n<!-- Financial. -->\n| amount = {{USD|649 billion|link=yes}} (2018) ([[List of countries by military expenditures|ranked 1st]])\n|percent_GDP=3.2% ([[List of countries by military expenditures|2018]])\n<!-- Industrial. -->\n| domestic_suppliers = [[List of United States defense contractors|List]]\n| foreign_suppliers =\n| imports =\n| exports =\n<!-- Related articles. -->\n| history =[[Military history of the United States]]\n{{hidden \n|''List of engagements''\n|[[American Revolutionary War]]<br>[[Whiskey Rebellion]]<br>[[American Indian Wars|Indian Wars]]<br>[[Barbary Wars]]<br>[[War of 1812]]<br>[[Patriot War]]<br>[[Mexican\u2013American War]]<br>[[Utah War]]<br>[[Cortina Troubles]]<br>[[Reform War]]<br>[[American Civil War]]\n* [[New York City draft riots]]\n[[Las Cuevas War]]<br>[[Spanish\u2013American War]]<br>[[Banana Wars]]<br>[[Philippine\u2013American War]]<br>[[Boxer Rebellion]]<br>[[Border War (1910\u20131918)|Border War]]<br>[[World War I]]\n** [[Western Front (World War I)|Western European Front]]\n[[Allied intervention in the Russian Civil War|Russian Civil War]]<br>[[World War II]]\n** [[Pacific War]]\n** [[North Africa Campaign|North African Front]]\n** [[Italian campaign (World War II)|Italian Front]]\n** [[Defense of the Reich|Combined Air Offensive]]\n** [[Western Front (World War II)|Western European Front]]\n[[Cold War]]\n* [[Puerto Rican Nationalist Party Revolts of the 1950s|Puerto Rican Nationalist Revolts]]\n* [[Korean War]]\n* [[1958 Lebanon crisis]]\n* [[Dominican Civil War]]\n* [[Bay of Pigs Invasion]]\n* [[Cuban Missile Crisis]]\n* [[Vietnam War]]\n* [[Korean DMZ Conflict (1966\u201369)|Korean DMZ Conflict]]\n* [[Operation Eagle Claw]]\n* [[Multinational Force in Lebanon|Multinational Force Lebanon]]\n* [[Invasion of Grenada]]\n* [[Operation Golden Pheasant]]\n* [[United States Invasion of Panama|Invasion of Panama]]\n[[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]<br>[[Somali Civil War]]\n* [[Operation Gothic Serpent]]\n* [[Battle of Mogadishu (1993)|Battle of Mogadishu]]\n[[Bosnian War]]\n* [[Operation Deliberate Force]]\n* [[Operation Deny Flight]]\n[[Kosovo War]]\n* [[Operation Allied Force]]\n[[War on Terror|Global War on Terrorism]]\n* [[Operation Enduring Freedom]]\n** [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]\n** [[Operation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Philippines|Philippines]]\n** [[Operation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Horn of Africa|Horn of Africa]]\n** [[Operation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Trans Sahara|Trans Sahara]]\n* [[2003 invasion of Iraq]]\n* [[Iraq War]]\n* [[War in North-West Pakistan]]\n[[Hurricane Katrina disaster relief#Military|Military deployment after Hurricane Katrina]]<br>[[Pakistan\u2013United States skirmishes]]<br>[[Operation Inherent Resolve|War on ISIL]]<br>\n[[List of wars involving the United States|Other]]\n| headerstyle=background:#b0c4de\n| style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| ranks =\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT CHANGE THE ORDER OF PRECEDENCE HERE OR ELSEWHERE IN THE ARTICLE. Please read the talk page as to why. -->\n'''Commissioned officer'''\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Army officer rank insignia|Army officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Marine Corps rank insignia|Marine Corps officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Navy officer rank insignia|Navy officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Air Force officer rank insignia|Air Force officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Coast Guard officer rank insignia|Coast Guard officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[Public Health Service Commissioned Corps#Commissioned officers|Public Health Service officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps#Commissioned officers|NOAA Corps officer]]}}\n\n'''Warrant officer'''\n* {{nowrap|[[Warrant officer (United_States)#Army|Army warrant officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[Warrant officer (United_States)#Marine Corps|Marine Corps warrant officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[Warrant officer (United_States)#Navy|Navy warrant officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[Warrant officer (United_States)#Air Force|Air Force warrant officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[Warrant officer (United_States)#Coast Guard|Coast Guard warrant officer]]}}\n\n'''Enlisted'''\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Army enlisted rank insignia|Army enlisted]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Marine Corps rank insignia|Marine Corps enlisted]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[List of United States Navy enlisted rates|Navy enlisted]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Air Force enlisted rank insignia|Air Force enlisted]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[List of United States Coast Guard enlisted ranks|Coast Guard enlisted]]}}\n}}\n\nThe [[United States]] has eight federal [[uniformed services]] that [[Officer (armed forces)|commission]] officers as defined by [[Title 10 of the United States Code|Title 10]] and subsequently structured and organized by Title 10, [[Title 14 of the United States Code|Title 14]], [[Title 32 of the United States Code|Title 32]] and [[Title 42 of the United States Code|Title 42]] of the [[United States Code|U.S. Code]].\n\n==Uniformed services==\nThe uniformed services are, in order of precedence, when in formations:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biotech.law.lsu.edu/blaw/dodd/corres/pdf2/d10058p.pdf|title= DoD Directive 1005.8}}</ref>\n# [[United States Army]]\n# [[United States Marine Corps]]\n# [[United States Navy]]\n# [[United States Air Force]]\n# [[United States Coast Guard]]\n# [[United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps]]\n# [[NOAA Commissioned Officer Corps|National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps]]\n:* [[United States Space Force]] (The precedence of the Space Force has not yet been determined.)\n\nEach of the uniformed services is administratively headed by a [[United States federal executive departments|federal executive department]] and its corresponding civilian [[United States Cabinet|Cabinet]] leader.\n\n==Federal executive departments==\n\n===United States Department of Defense (DoD)===\n'''Department of the Army (DA)'''\n* [[United States Army]] (USA): 14 June 1775\n'''Department of the Navy (DON)'''\n* [[United States Marine Corps]] (USMC): 10 November 1775\n* [[United States Navy]] (USN): 13 October 1775\n'''Department of the Air Force (DAF)'''\n* [[United States Air Force]] (USAF): 18 September 1947\n* [[United States Space Force]] (USSF): 20 December 2019\n\nThe order of precedence within the U.S. Department of Defense is set by DoD Directive 1005.8 and is not dependent on the date of creation by the U.S. Congress.\n\n===United States Department of Homeland Security (DHS)===\n* [[United States Coast Guard]] (USCG): 4 August 1790\n\nPrior to 1967, the U.S. Coast Guard was a part of the [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Department of the Treasury]]. In 1967 it became a part of the [[United States Department of Transportation|U.S. Department of Transportation]]. In 2002 it was placed under the DHS. During time of war it may be transferred to the Department of the Navy, under the Department of Defense.\n\n===United States Department of Health and Human Services (HHS)===\n* [[United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps]] (PHSCC): 4 January 1889\n\nThe Corps is headed by the [[Surgeon General of the United States]].\n\n===United States Department of Commerce (DOC)===\n* [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps]] (NOAA Corps): 22 May 1917.\n\nThe NOAA Corps was created as the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey Corps, a component of the [[United States Coast and Geodetic Survey]], on 22 May 1917. It was removed from the Coast and Geodetic Survey and became a component of the [[Environmental Science Services Administration]] (ESSA) as the Environmental Science Services Administration Corps (ESSA Corps) upon the establishment of ESSA on 13 July 1965. The ESSA Corps became the NOAA Corps as a component of NOAA when ESSA was abolished and NOAA simultaneously was created on 3 October 1970. Under all three names, the Corps has been an element of the Department of Commerce throughout its existence.\n\n==Statutory definition==\nThe eight [[uniformed services]] are defined by {{uscsub|10|101|a|5}}:\n\n<blockquote><poem>The term \"uniformed services\" means\u2014\n:(A) the armed forces;\n:(B) the commissioned corps of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration; and\n:(C) the commissioned corps of the Public Health Service.\n</poem></blockquote>\n\nThe six uniformed services that make up the [[United States Armed Forces]] are defined in the previous clause {{uscsub|10|101|a|4}}{{efn|Amended by National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2020.<ref>{{cite act |url=https://docs.house.gov/billsthisweek/20191209/CRPT-116hrpt333.pdf |title = [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2020]] |legislature = United States Congress |year = 2019 |article = IX, Subtitle D, Section 952(b)(2) |article-type = Title | page = 904}}</ref>}}<!--Keep note until law.cornell.edu updates text as amended.-->\n\n<blockquote>The term \"armed forces\" means the Army, Navy, Air Force, Marine Corps, Space Force, and Coast Guard.</blockquote>\n\nAll eight uniformed services are subject to the provisions of 10 USC 1408, the Uniformed Services Former Spouses Protection Act (USFSPA).\n\n==U.S. Armed Forces==\nSix of the uniformed services make up the [[United States Armed Forces|U.S. Armed Forces]], five of which are within the [[United States Department of Defense|U.S. Department of Defense]]. The Coast Guard is part of the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] and has both military and [[Law enforcement agency|law enforcement]] duties. [[Title 14 of the United States Code|Title 14]] states that the Coast Guard is part of the armed forces at all times, making it the only branch of the military outside the Department of Defense. During a declared state of war, however, the President or Congress may direct that the Coast Guard operate as part of the Department of the Navy.<ref>{{usc|14|3}}</ref> The U.S. Public Health Service Commissioned Corps, along with the NOAA Commissioned Corps, operate under military rules with the exception of the applicability of the [[Uniform Code of Military Justice]], to which they are subject only when militarized by executive order or while detailed to any component of the armed forces.<ref>{{Cite web|title=UCMJ S 802. Art. 2. Subs. (a). Para. (8) |url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/10/802-}}</ref>\n\n[[Reserve components of the United States Armed Forces]] are all members of the military who serve in a reserve capacity. The [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] is an additional reserve military component of the Army and Air Force, respectively, and is composed of National Guard units, which operate under [[Title 32 of the United States Code|Title 32]] and under state authority as the [[Army National Guard]] and [[Air National Guard]]. The militia that later became the National Guard was first formed in the [[Colony of Virginia]] in 1607 and is the oldest uniformed military force founded in the [[New World]]. The National Guard can also be mobilized by the President to operate under Federal authority through [[Title 10 of the United States Code|Title 10]]. When acting under federal direction, the National Guard is managed by the [[National Guard Bureau]], which is a joint Army and Air Force activity under the Department of Defense,<ref name=\"H.R. 4986\">{{cite web|url = http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?tab=main&bill=h110-4986|title= H.R. 4986: National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"H.R. 4986 text\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/billtext.xpd?bill=h110-4986|title= H.R. 4986: National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2008 full text}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/billtext.xpd?bill=h110-4986|title= SEC. 1812. ESTABLISHMENT OF NATIONAL GUARD BUREAU AS JOINT ACTIVITY OF THE DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE}}</ref> with a 4-star [[General (United States)|general]]<ref name=\"H.R. 4986\"/><ref name=\"H.R. 4986 text\"/> from the Army or Air Force appointed as its top leader. However, in Federal service command and control of National Guard organizations will fall under the designated Geographic or Functional Combatant Commander. The National Guard of the United States serves as a reserve component for both the Army and the Air Force and can be called up for federal active duty in times of war or national emergencies.<ref name=\"H.R. 4986\"/><ref name=\"H.R. 4986 text\"/>\n\n==Non-armed uniformed services==\n* The [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps]] (NOAA Corps) is a uniformed branch of the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA), which is under the [[United States Department of Commerce|Department of Commerce]].\n* The [[United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps]] (PHSCC) is the uniformed personnel system of the [[United States Public Health Service]], which is under the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|Department of Health and Human Services]].\n\nCommissioned officers of NOAA and PHS wear [[uniform]]s that are derived from U.S. Navy and Coast Guard uniforms, except that the commissioning devices, buttons, and insignia reflect their specific service. Uniformed officers of NOAA and PHS are paid on the same scale as members of the armed services with respective rank and time-in-grade. Additionally, PHS Officers are covered by the [[Uniformed Services Employment and Reemployment Act]] and the [[Servicemembers Civil Relief Act]] (formerly the Soldiers and Sailors Civil Relief Act).\n\nPHS and NOAA consist of [[commissioned officer]]s only and have no [[warrant officer]] ranks or [[enlisted ranks]]. Commissioned officers of the PHS and NOAA may be militarized by the President.<ref>PHS is under Title 42 & 46 U.S.C.</ref> Because they are commissioned officers, they can be classified as [[prisoners of war]] under the [[Geneva Conventions]], if captured by a [[belligerent]] entity. The [[United States Coast and Geodetic Survey]] (USC&GS), a predecessor to NOAA, originally began commissioning its officers so that if captured while engaged in battlefield surveying, they would be protected under the [[Law of Armed Conflict]] and could not be tried or executed as [[espionage|spies]]. The USC&GS Commissioned Officer Corps became the Environmental Science Services Administration Corps (ESSA Corps), upon the creation of the [[Environmental Science Services Administration]] (ESSA) on 13 July 1965, then became the NOAA Corps upon the creation of NOAA on 3 October 1970. The PHS traces its origins to [[Marine Hospital Service|a system of marine hospitals]] created by \"[[An Act for the relief of sick and disabled seamen]]\", passed by Congress in 1798; it adopted a military model of organization in 1871.<ref>''[[United States Code]]. Title 5. Part III. Chapter 21. S 2101''.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surgeongeneral.gov/about/history/ |title=History of the Office of Surgeon General |accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[United States Merchant Marine]]\n* [[Merchant Marine Reserve]]\n* [[United States Maritime Service]]\n* [[Civil Air Patrol]]\n* [[United States Coast Guard Auxiliary]]\n* [[State Defense Forces]]\n* [[Military badges of the United States]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Uniformed services of the United States}}\n{{US military navbox}}\n{{US Army navbox}}\n{{US Marine Corps navbox}}\n{{US Navy navbox}}\n{{US Air Force navbox}}\n{{United States Space Force}}\n{{US Coast Guard navbox}}\n{{United States Department of Health and Human Services}}\n{{United States Department of Commerce}}\n\n[[Category:Uniformed services of the United States| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2014}}\n{{short description|\nUniformed service of the United States of America}}\n{{Infobox national military\n|country=The United States\n|name=Uniformed services of the United States\n|image= [[File:Military service mark of the United States Army.svg|80px]] [[File:Emblem of the United States Marine Corps.svg|80px]] [[File:Emblem of the United States Navy.svg|80px]] [[File:Military service mark of the United States Air Force.svg|80px]] [[File:Seal of the United States Space Force.svg|80px]] [[File:Seal of the United States Coast Guard.svg|80px]] [[File:Seal of the USPHS Commissioned Corps.jpg|80px]] [[File:NOAA Commissioned Corps.png|80px]] \n|caption= The emblems of the eight U.S. uniformed services\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1775|06|14|df=yes}}<ref>With the establishment of the [[Continental Army]].</ref>\n| current_form =\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT CHANGE THE ORDER OF PRECEDENCE HERE OR ELSEWHERE IN THE ARTICLE. Please read the talk page as to why. -->\n|branches={{plainlist|\n* {{Army|United States|size=23px|name=U.S. Army}}\n* {{Marines|United States|size=23px|name=U.S. Marine Corps}}\n* {{Naval|United States|size=23px|name=U.S. Navy}}\n* {{Air force|United States|size=23px|name=U.S. Air Force}}\n* [[File:Seal of the United States Space Force.svg|25px]] [[United States Space Force|U.S. Space Force]]\n* {{Flag|United States Coast Guard|size=23px|name=U.S. Coast Guard}}\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the United States Public Health Service.svg|size=23px}} [[United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps|USPHS Commissioned Corps]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the NOAA Commissioned Officer Corps.svg|size=23px}} [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps|NOAA Commissioned Officer Corps]]\n}}\n| headquarters = \n<!-- Leadership. -->\n|commander-in-chief={{Flagicon image|Flag of the President of the United States of America.svg|size=23px}} [[Donald Trump]]\n|commander-in-chief_title=[[President of the United States|President]] \n|minister={{plainlist|\n* {{Flagicon image|USSecDefflag.svg|size=23px}} [[Mark Esper]] ([[United States Secretary of Defense|DoD]])\n* {{Flagicon image|Flag of the United States Secretary of Homeland Security.svg|size=23px}} [[Chad Wolf]] ([[United States Secretary of Homeland Security|DHS]])\n* {{Flagicon image|Flag of the United States Secretary of Health and Human Services.svg|size=23px}} [[Alex Azar]] ([[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services|HHS]])\n* {{Flagicon image|Flag of the United States Secretary of Commerce.svg|size=23px}} [[Wilbur Ross]] ([[United States Secretary of Commerce|DOC]])\n}}\n|minister_title=Federal department heads\n<!-- Manpower. -->\n| age = 17 with parental consent, 18 for voluntary service. Maximum age for first-time enlistment is 35 for the Army,<ref name=\"goarmy.com\">{{cite web|title=United States Army|url=http://www.goarmy.com/about/service-options/enlisted-soldiers-and-officers/enlisted-soldier.html|website=Goarmy.com|accessdate=18 June 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130629172147/http://www.goarmy.com/about/service-options/enlisted-soldiers-and-officers/enlisted-soldier.html|archivedate=29 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 28 for the Marine Corps, 34 for the Navy, 39 for the Air Force<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airforce.com/contact-us/faq/eligibility/#what-cut-off-age|title=Contact Us: Frequently Asked Questions - airforce.com|work=airforce.com|accessdate=1 April 2015}}</ref> and 27 for the Coast Guard.<ref name=USCGcareers>{{cite web|title=Plan Your Next Move to Become a Coast Guard Member|url=http://www.gocoastguard.com/active-duty-careers/enlisted-opportunities/plan-your-next-move|work=Enlisted Opportunities|publisher=U.S. Coast Guard|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref>\n| conscription =\n| active = 1,281,900\n| ranked = 3rd\n| reserve = 811,000\n| deployed =\n<!-- Financial. -->\n| amount = {{USD|649 billion|link=yes}} (2018) ([[List of countries by military expenditures|ranked 1st]])\n|percent_GDP=3.2% ([[List of countries by military expenditures|2018]])\n<!-- Industrial. -->\n| domestic_suppliers = [[List of United States defense contractors|List]]\n| foreign_suppliers =\n| imports =\n| exports =\n<!-- Related articles. -->\n| history =[[Military history of the United States]]\n{{hidden \n|''List of engagements''\n|[[American Revolutionary War]]<br>[[Whiskey Rebellion]]<br>[[American Indian Wars|Indian Wars]]<br>[[Barbary Wars]]<br>[[War of 1812]]<br>[[Patriot War]]<br>[[Mexican\u2013American War]]<br>[[Utah War]]<br>[[Cortina Troubles]]<br>[[Reform War]]<br>[[American Civil War]]\n* [[New York City draft riots]]\n[[Las Cuevas War]]<br>[[Spanish\u2013American War]]<br>[[Banana Wars]]<br>[[Philippine\u2013American War]]<br>[[Boxer Rebellion]]<br>[[Border War (1910\u20131918)|Border War]]<br>[[World War I]]\n** [[Western Front (World War I)|Western European Front]]\n[[Allied intervention in the Russian Civil War|Russian Civil War]]<br>[[World War II]]\n** [[Pacific War]]\n** [[North Africa Campaign|North African Front]]\n** [[Italian campaign (World War II)|Italian Front]]\n** [[Defense of the Reich|Combined Air Offensive]]\n** [[Western Front (World War II)|Western European Front]]\n[[Cold War]]\n* [[Puerto Rican Nationalist Party Revolts of the 1950s|Puerto Rican Nationalist Revolts]]\n* [[Korean War]]\n* [[1958 Lebanon crisis]]\n* [[Dominican Civil War]]\n* [[Bay of Pigs Invasion]]\n* [[Cuban Missile Crisis]]\n* [[Vietnam War]]\n* [[Korean DMZ Conflict (1966\u201369)|Korean DMZ Conflict]]\n* [[Operation Eagle Claw]]\n* [[Multinational Force in Lebanon|Multinational Force Lebanon]]\n* [[Invasion of Grenada]]\n* [[Operation Golden Pheasant]]\n* [[United States Invasion of Panama|Invasion of Panama]]\n[[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]<br>[[Somali Civil War]]\n* [[Operation Gothic Serpent]]\n* [[Battle of Mogadishu (1993)|Battle of Mogadishu]]\n[[Bosnian War]]\n* [[Operation Deliberate Force]]\n* [[Operation Deny Flight]]\n[[Kosovo War]]\n* [[Operation Allied Force]]\n[[War on Terror|Global War on Terrorism]]\n* [[Operation Enduring Freedom]]\n** [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]\n** [[Operation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Philippines|Philippines]]\n** [[Operation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Horn of Africa|Horn of Africa]]\n** [[Operation Enduring Freedom \u2013 Trans Sahara|Trans Sahara]]\n* [[2003 invasion of Iraq]]\n* [[Iraq War]]\n* [[War in North-West Pakistan]]\n[[Hurricane Katrina disaster relief#Military|Military deployment after Hurricane Katrina]]<br>[[Pakistan\u2013United States skirmishes]]<br>[[Operation Inherent Resolve|War on ISIL]]<br>\n[[List of wars involving the United States|Other]]\n| headerstyle=background:#b0c4de\n| style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| ranks =\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT CHANGE THE ORDER OF PRECEDENCE HERE OR ELSEWHERE IN THE ARTICLE. Please read the talk page as to why. -->\n'''Commissioned officer'''\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Army officer rank insignia|Army officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Marine Corps rank insignia|Marine Corps officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Navy officer rank insignia|Navy officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Air Force officer rank insignia|Air Force officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Coast Guard officer rank insignia|Coast Guard officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[Public Health Service Commissioned Corps#Commissioned officers|Public Health Service officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps#Commissioned officers|NOAA Corps officer]]}}\n\n'''Warrant officer'''\n* {{nowrap|[[Warrant officer (United_States)#Army|Army warrant officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[Warrant officer (United_States)#Marine Corps|Marine Corps warrant officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[Warrant officer (United_States)#Navy|Navy warrant officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[Warrant officer (United_States)#Air Force|Air Force warrant officer]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[Warrant officer (United_States)#Coast Guard|Coast Guard warrant officer]]}}\n\n'''Enlisted'''\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Army enlisted rank insignia|Army enlisted]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Marine Corps rank insignia|Marine Corps enlisted]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[List of United States Navy enlisted rates|Navy enlisted]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[United States Air Force enlisted rank insignia|Air Force enlisted]]}}\n* {{nowrap|[[List of United States Coast Guard enlisted ranks|Coast Guard enlisted]]}}\n}}\n\nThe [[United States]] has eight federal [[uniformed services]] that [[Officer (armed forces)|commission]] officers as defined by [[Title 10 of the United States Code|Title 10]] and subsequently structured and organized by Title 10, [[Title 14 of the United States Code|Title 14]], [[Title 32 of the United States Code|Title 32]] and [[Title 42 of the United States Code|Title 42]] of the [[United States Code|U.S. Code]].\n\n==Uniformed services==\nThe uniformed services are, in order of precedence, when in formations:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biotech.law.lsu.edu/blaw/dodd/corres/pdf2/d10058p.pdf|title= DoD Directive 1005.8}}</ref>\n# [[United States Army]]\n# [[United States Marine Corps]]\n# [[United States Navy]]\n# [[United States Air Force]]\n# [[United States Coast Guard]]\n# [[United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps]]\n# [[NOAA Commissioned Officer Corps|National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps]]\n:* [[United States Space Force]] (The precedence of the Space Force has not yet been determined.)\n\nEach of the uniformed services is administratively headed by a [[United States federal executive departments|federal executive department]] and its corresponding civilian [[United States Cabinet|Cabinet]] leader.\n\n==Federal executive departments==\n\n===United States Department of Defense (DoD)===\n'''Department of the Army (DA)'''\n* [[United States Army]] (USA): 14 June 1775\n'''Department of the Navy (DON)'''\n* [[United States Marine Corps]] (USMC): 10 November 1775\n* [[United States Navy]] (USN): 13 October 1775\n'''Department of the Air Force (DAF)'''\n* [[United States Air Force]] (USAF): 18 September 1947\n* [[United States Space Force]] (USSF): 20 December 2019\n\nThe order of precedence within the U.S. Department of Defense is set by DoD Directive 1005.8 and is not dependent on the date of creation by the U.S. Congress.\n\n===United States Department of Homeland Security (DHS)===\n* [[United States Coast Guard]] (USCG): 4 August 1790\n\nPrior to 1967, the U.S. Coast Guard was a part of the [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Department of the Treasury]]. In 1967 it became a part of the [[United States Department of Transportation|U.S. Department of Transportation]]. In 2002 it was placed under the DHS. During time of war it may be transferred to the Department of the Navy, under the Department of Defense.\n\n===United States Department of Health and Human Services (HHS)===\n* [[United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps]] (PHSCC): 4 January 1889\n\nThe Corps is headed by the [[Surgeon General of the United States]].\n\n===United States Department of Commerce (DOC)===\n* [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps]] (NOAA Corps): 22 May 1917.\n\nThe NOAA Corps was created as the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey Corps, a component of the [[United States Coast and Geodetic Survey]], on 22 May 1917. It was removed from the Coast and Geodetic Survey and became a component of the [[Environmental Science Services Administration]] (ESSA) as the Environmental Science Services Administration Corps (ESSA Corps) upon the establishment of ESSA on 13 July 1965. The ESSA Corps became the NOAA Corps as a component of NOAA when ESSA was abolished and NOAA simultaneously was created on 3 October 1970. Under all three names, the Corps has been an element of the Department of Commerce throughout its existence.\n\n==Statutory definition==\nThe eight [[uniformed services]] are defined by {{uscsub|10|101|a|5}}:\n\n<blockquote><poem>The term \"uniformed services\" means\u2014\n:(A) the armed forces;\n:(B) the commissioned corps of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration; and\n:(C) the commissioned corps of the Public Health Service.\n</poem></blockquote>\n\nThe six uniformed services that make up the [[United States Armed Forces]] are defined in the previous clause {{uscsub|10|101|a|4}}{{efn|Amended by National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2020.<ref>{{cite act |url=https://docs.house.gov/billsthisweek/20191209/CRPT-116hrpt333.pdf |title = [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2020]] |legislature = United States Congress |year = 2019 |article = IX, Subtitle D, Section 952(b)(2) |article-type = Title | page = 904}}</ref>}}<!--Keep note until law.cornell.edu updates text as amended.-->\n\n<blockquote>The term \"armed forces\" means the Army, Navy, Air Force, Marine Corps, Space Force, and Coast Guard.</blockquote>\n\nAll eight uniformed services are subject to the provisions of 10 USC 1408, the Uniformed Services Former Spouses Protection Act (USFSPA).\n\n==U.S. Armed Forces==\nSix of the uniformed services make up the [[United States Armed Forces|U.S. Armed Forces]], five of which are within the [[United States Department of Defense|U.S. Department of Defense]]. The Coast Guard is part of the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] and has both military and [[Law enforcement agency|law enforcement]] duties. [[Title 14 of the United States Code|Title 14]] states that the Coast Guard is part of the armed forces at all times, making it the only branch of the military outside the Department of Defense. During a declared state of war, however, the President or Congress may direct that the Coast Guard operate as part of the Department of the Navy.<ref>{{usc|14|3}}</ref> The U.S. Public Health Service Commissioned Corps, along with the NOAA Commissioned Corps, operate under military rules with the exception of the applicability of the [[Uniform Code of Military Justice]], to which they are subject only when militarized by executive order or while detailed to any component of the armed forces.<ref>{{Cite web|title=UCMJ S 802. Art. 2. Subs. (a). Para. (8) |url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/10/802-}}</ref>\n\n[[Reserve components of the United States Armed Forces]] are all members of the military who serve in a reserve capacity. The [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] is an additional reserve military component of the Army and Air Force, respectively, and is composed of National Guard units, which operate under [[Title 32 of the United States Code|Title 32]] and under state authority as the [[Army National Guard]] and [[Air National Guard]]. The militia that later became the National Guard was first formed in the [[Colony of Virginia]] in 1607 and is the oldest uniformed military force founded in the [[New World]]. The National Guard can also be mobilized by the President to operate under Federal authority through [[Title 10 of the United States Code|Title 10]]. When acting under federal direction, the National Guard is managed by the [[National Guard Bureau]], which is a joint Army and Air Force activity under the Department of Defense,<ref name=\"H.R. 4986\">{{cite web|url = http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?tab=main&bill=h110-4986|title= H.R. 4986: National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"H.R. 4986 text\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/billtext.xpd?bill=h110-4986|title= H.R. 4986: National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2008 full text}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/billtext.xpd?bill=h110-4986|title= SEC. 1812. ESTABLISHMENT OF NATIONAL GUARD BUREAU AS JOINT ACTIVITY OF THE DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE}}</ref> with a 4-star [[General (United States)|general]]<ref name=\"H.R. 4986\"/><ref name=\"H.R. 4986 text\"/> from the Army or Air Force appointed as its top leader. However, in Federal service command and control of National Guard organizations will fall under the designated Geographic or Functional Combatant Commander. The National Guard of the United States serves as a reserve component for both the Army and the Air Force and can be called up for federal active duty in times of war or national emergencies.<ref name=\"H.R. 4986\"/><ref name=\"H.R. 4986 text\"/>\n\n==Non-armed uniformed services==\n* The [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps]] (NOAA Corps) is a uniformed branch of the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA), which is under the [[United States Department of Commerce|Department of Commerce]].\n* The [[United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps]] (PHSCC) is the uniformed personnel system of the [[United States Public Health Service]], which is under the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|Department of Health and Human Services]].\n\nCommissioned officers of NOAA and PHS wear [[uniform]]s that are derived from U.S. Navy and Coast Guard uniforms, except that the commissioning devices, buttons, and insignia reflect their specific service. Uniformed officers of NOAA and PHS are paid on the same scale as members of the armed services with respective rank and time-in-grade. Additionally, PHS Officers are covered by the [[Uniformed Services Employment and Reemployment Act]] and the [[Servicemembers Civil Relief Act]] (formerly the Soldiers and Sailors Civil Relief Act).\n\nPHS and NOAA consist of [[commissioned officer]]s only and have no [[warrant officer]] ranks or [[enlisted ranks]]. Commissioned officers of the PHS and NOAA may be militarized by the President.<ref>PHS is under Title 42 & 46 U.S.C.</ref> Because they are commissioned officers, they can be classified as [[prisoners of war]] under the [[Geneva Conventions]], if captured by a [[belligerent]] entity. The [[United States Coast and Geodetic Survey]] (USC&GS), a predecessor to NOAA, originally began commissioning its officers so that if captured while engaged in battlefield surveying, they would be protected under the [[Law of Armed Conflict]] and could not be tried or executed as [[espionage|spies]]. The USC&GS Commissioned Officer Corps became the Environmental Science Services Administration Corps (ESSA Corps), upon the creation of the [[Environmental Science Services Administration]] (ESSA) on 13 July 1965, then became the NOAA Corps upon the creation of NOAA on 3 October 1970. The PHS traces its origins to [[Marine Hospital Service|a system of marine hospitals]] created by \"[[An Act for the relief of sick and disabled seamen]]\", passed by Congress in 1798; it adopted a military model of organization in 1871.<ref>''[[United States Code]]. Title 5. Part III. Chapter 21. S 2101''.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surgeongeneral.gov/about/history/ |title=History of the Office of Surgeon General |accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[United States Merchant Marine]]\n* [[Merchant Marine Reserve]]\n* [[United States Maritime Service]]\n* [[Civil Air Patrol]]\n* [[United States Coast Guard Auxiliary]]\n* [[State Defense Forces]]\n* [[Military badges of the United States]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Uniformed services of the United States}}\n{{US military navbox}}\n{{US Army navbox}}\n{{US Marine Corps navbox}}\n{{US Navy navbox}}\n{{US Air Force navbox}}\n{{United States Space Force}}\n{{US Coast Guard navbox}}\n{{United States Department of Health and Human Services}}\n{{United States Department of Commerce}}\n\n[[Category:Uniformed services of the United States| ]]\n", "name_user": "Illegitimate Barrister", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:not a ref.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniformed_services_of_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!", "text_new": "{{One source|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox television season\n| season_number        = \n| bgcolour             = #006600\n| image                = ReturnofAlloAlloTitleCard.jpg\n| image_upright        = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| starring = \n| country              = United Kingdom\n| num_episodes         = 1\n| network              = [[BBC Two|BBC2]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2007|04|28|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = \n| episode_list         = List of 'Allo 'Allo! episodes\n}}\n'''''The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!''''' is a one-off special episode of the sitcom '''''[['Allo 'Allo!]]'''''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/tvandradioblog/2007/apr/25/alloalloiwishitwouldsay|title='Allo 'Allo? I wish it would say goodbye for good|first=Simon|last=Swift|date=25 April 2007|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\n''The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!'' was broadcast live on [[BBC Two]] on 28 April 2007 at 9pm.<ref>{{cite web|title=Radio Times listing for original transmission of \"The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!\", archived at BBC Genome Project|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/7da24b7ab48f4b19a39186936bfb847c|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The storyline involves Ren\u00e9 writing his memoirs after the war. The new scenes are interspersed with clips from the original series and interviews with the original cast. The episode features [[Gorden Kaye]], [[Vicki Michelle]], [[Sue Hodge]], [[Kirsten Cooke]], [[Arthur Bostrom]], [[Guy Siner]], [[Robin Parkinson]], [[John D. Collins]] and [[Nicholas Frankau]] reprising their original roles. In addition, [[Sam Kelly]] and [[Richard Gibson]] appear as themselves. [[Jeremy Lloyd]] is among the script-writing team.\n\n== Plot ==\nA one-off special. Ren\u00e9 is writing his memoirs and needs help to fill in the \"big gaps\".\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Gorden Kaye]] as Ren\u00e9 Artois<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/gorden-kaye-returns-for-allo-allo-special-7266855.html|title=Gorden Kaye returns for 'Allo 'Allo special|website=www.standard.co.uk}}</ref>\n* [[Vicki Michelle]] as [[Yvette Carte-Blanche]]\n* [[Sue Hodge]] as [[Mimi Labonq]]\n* [[Kirsten Cooke]] as [[Michelle Dubois ('Allo 'Allo!)|Michelle Dubois]]\n* [[Arthur Bostrom]] as [[Officer Crabtree]]\n* [[Guy Siner]] as [[Lieutenant Hubert Gruber]]\n* [[Robin Parkinson]] as [[Monsieur Ernest LeClerc]]\n* [[John D. Collins]] as [[Officer Fairfax]]\n* [[Nicholas Frankau]] as [[Officer Carstairs]]\n* [[Richard Gibson]] as Himself\n* [[Sam Kelly]] as Himself\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* {{British Comedy Guide|tv|the_return_of_allo_allo}}\n* {{IMDb title|1002509}}\n\n{{'Allo 'Allo!}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Return Of 'Allo 'Allo!, The}}\n[[Category:'Allo 'Allo!]]\n[[Category:2007 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:2007 in British television]]\n[[Category:Television episodes set in France]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about World War II]]\n\n\n{{comedy-tv-episode-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{One source|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox television season\n| season_number        = \n| bgcolour             = #006600\n| image                = ReturnofAlloAlloTitleCard.jpg\n| image_upright        = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| starring = \n| country              = United Kingdom\n| num_episodes         = 1\n| network              = [[BBC Two|BBC2]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2007|04|28|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = \n| episode_list         = List of 'Allo 'Allo! episodes\n}}\n'''''The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!''''' is a one-off special episode of the sitcom '''''[['Allo 'Allo!]]'''''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/tvandradioblog/2007/apr/25/alloalloiwishitwouldsay|title='Allo 'Allo? I wish it would say goodbye for good|first=Simon|last=Swift|date=25 April 2007|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\n''The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!'' was broadcast live on [[BBC Two]] on 28 April 2007 at 9pm.<ref>{{cite web|title=Radio Times listing for original transmission of \"The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!\", archived at BBC Genome Project|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/7da24b7ab48f4b19a39186936bfb847c|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The storyline involves Ren\u00e9 writing his memoirs after the war. The new scenes are interspersed with clips from the original series and interviews with the original cast. The episode features [[Gorden Kaye]], [[Vicki Michelle]], [[Sue Hodge]], [[Kirsten Cooke]], [[Arthur Bostrom]], [[Guy Siner]], [[Robin Parkinson]], [[John D. Collins]] and [[Nicholas Frankau]] reprising their original roles. In addition, [[Sam Kelly]] and [[Richard Gibson]] appear as themselves. [[Jeremy Lloyd]] is among the script-writing team.\n\n== Plot ==\nA one-off special. Ren\u00e9 is writing his memoirs and needs help to fill in the \"big gaps\".\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Gorden Kaye]] as Ren\u00e9 Artois<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/gorden-kaye-returns-for-allo-allo-special-7266855.html|title=Gorden Kaye returns for 'Allo 'Allo special|website=www.standard.co.uk}}</ref>\n* [[Vicki Michelle]] as [[Yvette Carte-Blanche]]\n* [[Sue Hodge]] as [[Mimi Labonq]]\n* [[Kirsten Cooke]] as [[Michelle Dubois ('Allo 'Allo!)|Michelle Dubois]]\n* [[Arthur Bostrom]] as [[Officer Crabtree]]\n* [[Guy Siner]] as [[Lieutenant Hubert Gruber]]\n* [[Robin Parkinson]] as [[Monsieur Ernest LeClerc]]\n* [[John D. Collins]] as [[Officer Fairfax]]\n* [[Nicholas Frankau]] as [[Officer Carstairs]]\n* [[Richard Gibson]] as Himself\n* [[Sam Kelly]] as Himself\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* {{British Comedy Guide|tv|the_return_of_allo_allo}}\n* {{IMDb title|1002509}}\n\n{{'Allo 'Allo!}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Return Of 'All